Log-normalizing Data

{% raw %}

lognorm[source]

lognorm(reads)

Standardize read counts by calculating reads per million, adding a pseudo-count of one, and taking the log2

reads: numpy or pandas array | returns: numpy or pandas array

{% endraw %} {% raw %}

lognorm_columns[source]

lognorm_columns(reads_df, columns)

Calculate lognorms for specified columns

reads_df: dataframe | columns: list | returns: lognorm dataframe

{% endraw %} {% raw %}
{% endraw %}

To demonstrate the functionality of this module we'll use read counts from Sanson et al. 2018.

{% raw %}

To mitigate this tail and account for sequencing biases we log-normalize read counts by taking $$\log_2 \bigg ( \frac{\text{reads}}{\text{total reads in condition}} * 10^6 + 1 \bigg )$$

{% raw %} 
lognorms = lognorm_columns(reads_df=read_counts, columns=['pDNA', 'A375_RepA', 'A375_RepB'])
sns.kdeplot(lognorms['pDNA'])

<AxesSubplot:xlabel='pDNA', ylabel='Density'>
{% endraw %}

filter_pdna[source]

filter_pdna(lognorm_df, pdna_cols, z_low=-3, z_high=None)

Filter the lognorm dataframe based on the z_scored lognorms of pDNA

lognorm_df: dataframe | pdna_cols: list | z_low: int or None, lower range of z-scores to filter | z_high: int or None, upper range of z-scores to filter | returns: filtered dataframe

{% endraw %} {% raw %}
{% endraw %}

Note that there's a small number of sgRNAs with low pDNA abundance. We'll filter out any sgRNAs with lognormed pDNA less than the mean minus 3 standard deviations.

{% raw %} 
filtered_lognorms = filter_pdna(lognorm_df=lognorms, pdna_cols=['pDNA'])
lognorms.shape[0] - filtered_lognorms.shape[0]

Calculate log-fold changes

{% raw %}

calculate_lfcs[source]

calculate_lfcs(lognorm_df, ref_col=None, target_cols=None, ref_map=None)

Calculate log-fold changes between reference column and target columns

lognorm_df: dataframe | ref_col: str or None, if str then target_col must also be present | target_col: list or None | ref_map: dict or None, key-value pairs correspond to target-reference conditions | returns: dataframe with log-fold changes

{% endraw %} {% raw %}
{% endraw %}

We'll calculate log-fold changes from the pDNA reference. Since we only have one reference condition we can supply the calculate_lfcs function with the ref_col and target_cols arguments.

{% raw %} 
lfc_df = calculate_lfcs(lognorm_df=filtered_lognorms, ref_col='pDNA', target_cols=['A375_RepA', 'A375_RepB'])
{% endraw %}

Alternatively we can supply a ref_map, which is useful when we have more than one reference condition

{% raw %} 
lfc_df2 = calculate_lfcs(filtered_lognorms, ref_map = {'A375_RepA': 'pDNA', 'A375_RepB': 'pDNA'})
assert lfc_df.equals(lfc_df2)
{% endraw %}

{% endraw %}

We provide two methods for evaluating significance from log-fold change values:

  1. Z-score from a set of negative controls
  2. Calculate a probability from a set of negative and positive controls

For both scoring methods, you can input either a regex or a list of genes to define gene sets

{% raw %}

annotated_lfcs: dataframe, merged lfcs and annotations | controls: str or list of str or None, if string then interpreted as a regex otherwise interpreted as a list of gene names found in gene_col | gene_col: str, column which uniquely identifies a gene |

average_gene_lfcs(lfcs, annotations, gene_col, condition_col='condition', lfc_col='avg_lfc', merge_on=None, lfc_merge_on=None, annotation_merge_on=None, z_score_neg_ctls=False, z_score_neg_ctl_genes=None, scale_ctls=False, scale_neg_ctl_genes=None, scale_pos_ctl_genes=None)

Average log-fold changes of sgRNAs across genes

lfcs: dataframe | annotations: dataframe, mapping between sgRNAs and genes | gene_col: str, column which uniquely identifies a gene | condition_col: str, column which uniquely identifies experimental conditions | lfc_col: str, name of value to average | merge_on: str or None, name of sgRNA column to merge on. Must be present in both lfc and annotation dataframes if supplied, otherwise supply unique merge column to each | lfc_merge_on: str or None, name of sgRNA column to merge on | annotation_merge_on: str or None, name of sgRNA column to merge on. Present in annotation dataframe if supplied | z_score_neg_ctls: bool, z-score log-fold changes relative to negative controls | z_score_neg_ctl_genes: str, list of str, or None, if string then interpreted as a regex otherwise interpreted as a list of gene names found in gene_col. If None and z_score_neg_ctls is True, then uses all sgRNAs as controls | scale_ctls: bool, scale-lfcs by positive and negative controls | scale_neg_ctl_genes: str or list of str or None, if string then interpreted as a regex otherwise interpreted as a list of gene names found in gene_col | scale_pos_ctl_genes: str or list of str or None, if string then interpreted as a regex otherwise interpreted as a list of gene names found in gene_col | returns: dataframe, lfcs and (optionally) z-scores averaged by gene

We'll average the sgRNA log-fold changes by gene, and calculate z-scores and scaled scores

{% raw %} 
nonessential_genes = (pd.read_table('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/gpp-rnd/genesets/master/human/non-essential-genes-Hart2014.txt', 
                                    names=['gene'])
                      .gene)
essential_genes = (pd.read_table('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/gpp-rnd/genesets/master/human/essential-genes-Hart2015.txt', 
                                 names=['gene'])
                   .gene)
gene_lfcs = average_gene_lfcs(lfcs=avg_replicate_lfc_df, annotations=remapped_annotations, gene_col='Annotated Gene Symbol',
                              merge_on='sgRNA Sequence', z_score_neg_ctls=True,
                              z_score_neg_ctl_genes=nonessential_genes, scale_ctls=True, 
                              scale_neg_ctl_genes=nonessential_genes, scale_pos_ctl_genes=essential_genes)
assert np.abs(gene_lfcs.shape[0] - 20000) < 1000
# Do we score about the expect number of essential genes?
assert np.abs((gene_lfcs['probability_positive_control'] > 0.5).sum()/20000 - 0.2) < 0.1
assert gene_lfcs.sort_values('probability_positive_control', ascending=False).head(5)['Annotated Gene Symbol'].isin(essential_genes).sum() == 5
assert gene_lfcs[gene_lfcs.z_scored_avg_lfc < 0].sort_values('z_scored_avg_lfc_fdr_bh', ascending=True).head(5)['Annotated Gene Symbol'].isin(essential_genes).sum() == 5
# Do the two scoring mechanisms agree
gene_lfcs['z_essential'] = (gene_lfcs['z_scored_avg_lfc_fdr_bh'] < 0.1) & (gene_lfcs['z_scored_avg_lfc'] < 0)
gene_lfcs['p_essential'] = (gene_lfcs['probability_positive_control'] > 0.5)
scoring_overlap = gene_lfcs[['z_essential', 'p_essential']].value_counts().reset_index(name='n')
agree = scoring_overlap.loc[(scoring_overlap['z_essential'] == scoring_overlap['p_essential']), 'n'].sum()
disagree = scoring_overlap.loc[(scoring_overlap['z_essential'] != scoring_overlap['p_essential']), 'n'].sum()
accuracy = agree/(agree + disagree)
assert accuracy > 0.95
# Are controls centered around 0
control_z_scores = gene_lfcs.loc[gene_lfcs['Annotated Gene Symbol'].isin(nonessential_genes), 'z_scored_avg_lfc']
assert np.abs(control_z_scores.mean()) < 0.1
assert np.abs(control_z_scores.std() - 1) < 0.3

Calculate ROC-AUC between essential and non-essential genes

{% raw %}

get_roc_aucs[source]

get_roc_aucs(lfcs, tp_genes, fp_genes, gene_col, score_col=None, group_col=None, conditions=None)

Calculate the ROC-AUC between true positive and false positive gene sets. Must specificy score_col (and group_col optionally) or conditions

lfcs: dataframe | tp_genes: list-like, true positive genes | fp_genes: list-like, false positive genes | gene_col: str | score_col: str, column for ranking genes from smallest to largest. group_col: str or list, columns to use for grouping genes. conditions: list, columns for which to calculate ROC-AUCs returns: dataframe of roc_aucs

{% endraw %} {% raw %}
{% endraw %}

Finally, to evaluate the quality each screen, we'll calculate the ROC-AUC between essential and nonessential genes for each condition

We can calculate ROC-AUCs three different ways:

1) We can specify a group_col and score_col

{% raw %} 
roc_aucs = get_roc_aucs(lfcs=gene_lfcs, tp_genes=essential_genes, fp_genes=nonessential_genes, gene_col='Annotated Gene Symbol', 
                        group_col='condition', score_col='avg_lfc')
assert roc_aucs['ROC-AUC'][0] > 0.9
roc_aucs
condition ROC-AUC
0 A375 0.976175
{% endraw %}

2) Since we only have one condition we can also just supply the score_col

{% raw %} 
roc_aucs = get_roc_aucs(lfcs=gene_lfcs, tp_genes=essential_genes, fp_genes=nonessential_genes, gene_col='Annotated Gene Symbol', 
                        score_col='avg_lfc')
roc_aucs

0.976174694978823
{% endraw %}

Finally, we can specify conditions as a list of columns we want to calculate AUCs for

{% raw %} 
roc_aucs = get_roc_aucs(lfcs=gene_lfcs, tp_genes=essential_genes, fp_genes=nonessential_genes, gene_col='Annotated Gene Symbol',
                        conditions=['avg_lfc'])
roc_aucs
condition ROC-AUC

{% endraw %}

This is a useful approach when we want to quantify ROC-AUC at the guide level say
